Tens of thousands filled central London under the banner of “Unite the Kingdom,” waving flags, chanting “Christ is King,” and listening as Elon Musk addressed the crowd by video link alongside Tommy Robinson. The media framed it as extremism, but when ordinary people from pubs and football terraces gather in such numbers, what does it say about the legitimacy of the establishment? At a time when faith in politics has collapsed, new power is rising from unexpected places — tech billionaires, jailed activists, online movements — and Christianity itself re-emerges at the heart of rebellion. Is this chaos, or the first glimpse of a deeper transformation?
